 This transformation is called a projection;
	  it produces the shadow of the vector on the horizontal
	  axis.

subsection.p:
      The 

	linearity of matrix-vector multiplication

      provides the key to answering
      this question.  Remember that
      if A is a matrix, \vvec and \wvec vectors,
      and c a scalar, then

	\begin{aligned}
	A(c\vvec) \amp {}={} cA\vvec \\
	A(\vvec + \wvec) \amp {}={} A\vvec + A\wvec\text{.}
	\end{aligned}
      .
      This means that a matrix transformation T(\xvec) = A\xvec
      satisfies the corresponding linearity property:

	 Linearity of Matrix Transformations 



	    \begin{aligned}
	    T(c\vvec) \amp {}={} cT(\vvec) \\
	    T(\vvec + \wvec) \amp {}={} T(\vvec) + T(\wvec)\text{.}
	    \end{aligned}

      It turns out that, if T:\real^n\to\real^m satisfies these
      two linearity properties, then we can find a matrix A
      such that T(\xvec) = A\xvec.  In fact,  tells us how to form
      A; we simply write

	A = \left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
	T(\evec_1) \amp T(\evec_2) \amp \ldots T(\evec_n)
	\end{array}\right]
      .
      We will now check that T(\xvec) = A\xvec using the
      linearity of T:

	\begin{aligned}
	T(\xvec) = T\left(\fourvec{x_1}{x_2}{\vdots}{x_n}\right)
	\amp {}={}
	T(x_1\evec_1 + x_2\evec_2 + \ldots + x_n\evec_n) \\ \\
	\amp {}={}
	x_1T(\evec_1) + x_2T(\evec_2) + \ldots + x_nT(\evec_n) \\ \\
	\amp {}={}
	x_1A\evec_1 + x_2A\evec_2 + \ldots + x_nA\evec_n \\ \\
	\amp {}={}
	A(x_1\evec_1 + x_2\evec_2 + \ldots + x_n\evec_n) \\ \\
	\amp {}={}
	A\fourvec{x_1}{x_2}{\vdots}{x_n} \\ \\
	\amp {}={}
	A\xvec
	\end{aligned}
      .

statement.p:
We first need to know that T can be represented by a
matrix transformation, which means,
by , that we
need to verify the linearity properties:

  \begin{aligned}
  T(c\vvec) \amp {}={} cT(\vvec) \\
  T(\vvec + \wvec) \amp {}={} T(\vvec) + T(\wvec)\text{.}
  \end{aligned}

li.p:

  \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
  a \amp b \amp c \\
  d \amp e \amp f \\
  0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
  \end{array}\right]
  \threevec{x}{y}{1} =
  \cthreevec{ax+by+c}{dx+ey+f}{1}\text{,}

which shows that

  \begin{alignedat}{2}
  x' \amp {}={} ax+by+c \\
  y' \amp {}={} dx+ey+f\text{.} \\
  \end{alignedat}
